@Jay Benitah 
Hi Jay, 
I also wonder what fields are more apt for transitioning into online or hybrid jobs as well. Blue collar workers typically don't have higher than a college degree and thus dominate manual labor jobs, but with the rise of AI this may no longer be the case in upcoming years. How will the government ensure that progress in technology doesn't deter excess job opportunities?

@Morgan Comet 

Hey Morgan!

You made some really insightful observations and I happened to notice that your observations reflect many of the same aspects that I took note of during my own analysis of the graph. Additionally, being that you and I have both asked a very similar question regarding what the differences seem to be between high school and bachlor's program online commuting, I'd love to giev my perspective on a possible answer. I think one possibility for this major difference in online telecommuting could be the fact that many young adults between the ages of 20-25 have jobs outside of their normal education rotation. As such, it could be that it is simply less of a hassel for them to attend classes without having to spend an hour driving back and forth.

@Braison Comet 

Hey Braison,

Your question is very interesting and your observations about the bachelor's degree students working more online and relating it to the issues caused by the pandemic were really integrated! In regards to your question, I'd love to share my thoughts. I think some possibilities for jobs these students may have taken on could be internships or simple lower-paying jobs that require them to be further away from their campuses/institutions of study.
